Hammon. . . aditur: Jupiter Hammon, god of Thebes in Egypt, was represented as a ram with horns. Jupiter Capitolinus reigned in his temple on the Capitol, represented with a thunder- bolt in his hand, as Jupiter Optimus Maximus. As Jupiter Latiaris he received sacrifice from all the Latin communities in his grove on the Alban Mount (feriae Latinae). Jupiter Feretrius on the Capitol was among the oldest in Rome. Feretrius fr. ferire “ to strike '³ or sacrifice the victim which ratified the treaty or oath (foedus ferire). The stone (lapis, silex) used in formally striking the victim was kept in the temple. A later interpretation, how- ever, which Minucius seems to follow here, is in connexion with the spolia opima, the armour taken from the vanquished foe when the commander-in-chief of the Roman army engaged and overthrew in single combat the commander-in-chief of the enemy.
